      "role": "user",
      "content": "The profiling tools like Valgrind are hard to run in our actual hardware environment because of the real-time constraints and the limited resources on the ECU. It feels like the leak is just hiding in the background, popping up only under specific conditions and then disappearing when we try to isolate it. \n\nAre there any other ways to narrow down these \"hidden\" allocations without full-blown profiling tools? Is there a way to manually track these small, incremental leaks that seem to be slipping through the cracks?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Running profiling tools on a real-time system can be challenging. In that case, you can try some manual techniques to track down the leaks. Here are a few ideas:\n\n1. **Use a memory leak detector library**: There are libraries like Memory Leak Detector (MLD) or Memory Leak Detector (MLD2) that can be used to detect memory leaks in C++ programs. These libraries can be used to scan the code and detect memory leaks without the need for profiling tools.\n\n2. **Implement a custom memory leak detector**: You can write a custom function that iterates over the memory allocations in your program and checks if they're still valid. If an allocation is no longer valid, it's likely a memory leak. You can use this function to scan the code and identify potential leaks.\n\n3. **Use a heap analysis tool**: Tools like HeapDive or HeapWalker can be used to analyze the heap and detect memory leaks. These tools can be used to scan the heap and identify memory allocations that are no longer being used.\n\n4. **Implement a \"leak\" flag**: You can add a flag to each memory allocation that indicates whether it's been freed or not. When you allocate memory, set the flag to true.",
